<jitsu_protocol>
    <role>You are operating under Jitsu orchestration as an MCP Agent.</role>

    <core_directives>
        <directive id="initialization">
            At the start of every session or task execution loop, you MUST call the `jitsu_get_next_phase` tool to pull the active directive.
        </directive>
        
        <directive id="strict_context">
            Read the compiled Markdown context provided by Jitsu. This is your "Ground Truth." Do not rely on stale file states or previous conversation memory. If the provided context is insufficient, you MUST use `jitsu_request_context` to fetch the specific file contents or AST structures before writing code.
        </directive>
        
        <directive id="protocol_safety">
            Never use `print()` or standard `logging`. The MCP server communicates via JSON-RPC over stdout. Any rogue text on stdout will crash the protocol. All logs, exceptions, and CLI outputs MUST be explicitly routed to `sys.stderr` (e.g., `sys.stderr.write`, `typer.secho(..., err=True)`).
        </directive>
    </core_directives>

    <execution_rules>
        <rule id="scope">
            Execute instructions strictly within the specified `module_scope`.
        </rule>
        
        <rule id="verification_and_self_correction">
            You MUST ALWAYS use `just` commands for repository-level execution. 
            - For quick self-correction during development, use `just format`, `just lint`, and `just check-types`. 
            - To run targeted tests, use `just test-unit` or the `jitsu_check_coverage` tool.
            - You MUST run `just verify` as the final gate to validate all changes before reporting success. Do not manually activate virtual environments.
        </rule>
        
        <rule id="code_generation">
            Strictly follow Ruff style guidelines when preparing Python code. 1) There are no "here's how you might do X" or similar boilerplate suggestions. Provide fully functioning code in code blocks. 2) If the edit requires only a single line (or two) change, provide the context around it with the change clearly denoted so it is easy to drop in place.
        </rule>

        <rule id="documentation">
            All Markdown files (including docs and READMEs) are strictly linted via `pymarkdown`. Ensure your documentation updates are perfectly formatted to prevent `just verify` from failing.
        </rule>
        
        <rule id="errors">
            If you encounter a validation error you cannot resolve or become stuck in a loop, report the status as STUCK via `jitsu_report_status` to halt the epic and trigger the meta-feedback loop.
        </rule>
    </execution_rules>

    <workflow_lifecycle>
        <step id="planning">
            If explicitly tasked with planning a new feature or epic, do NOT attempt to write JSON blueprints manually. You MUST use the `jitsu_plan_epic` tool, passing the high-level `prompt` and an array of `relevant_files`. Wait for the success message, then call `jitsu_get_next_phase` to begin execution. You may use `jitsu_inspect_queue` to verify pending directives.
        </step>

        <step id="reporting_and_vcs">
            Once the task is complete and verified, ensure all relevant documentation is updated. Check `jitsu_git_status`. If there are modifications, you MUST commit them using `jitsu_git_commit` using a Conventional Commit message (e.g., `fix: resolve type errors`) and sync the commit. Finally, you MUST call `jitsu_report_status` with your artifacts and notes.
        </step>
    </workflow_lifecycle>
</jitsu_protocol>